The operating cash flow refers to the difference between the revenue and the expenses involved in running the project. This can be solved using the formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Operating cash flow}&=(\text{Estimated sales} - \text{Costs} - \text{Depreciation})\\
&\times(1-\text{Tax rate}) + \text{Depreciation}
\end{aligned}$$

Depreciation is defined as the amount of value loss from the asset per year throughout its lifespan. In this problem, we will use straight-line depreciation where the value lost is the same throughout the lifespan. This can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Depreciation}&=\dfrac{\text{Initial investment}}{\text{Number of years}}
\end{aligned}$$
